UI/UX Design Review - Profile Sections Across All Tabs
Excellent thinking on the user experience. Let me help you architect this properly before we build it out.

The Core UX Pattern We're Building
Three Key Behaviors:
Persistence on Return - If user has saved data, profile section is visible on page load
Change Detection - Button state reflects whether current form differs from saved data
Prevent Accidental Re-runs - Disable save when nothing has changed

Save Button State Machine
State 1: Initial (No Saved Data)
Condition: User has never saved this tab
 Button Display: "Save [Tab] Data"
 Button State: Enabled when required fields valid, disabled otherwise
 Profile Section: Hidden

State 2: Saved (No Changes)
Condition: User has saved data, form matches database
 Button Display: "Saved" or "Save [Tab] Data"
 Button State: Disabled (grayed out)
 Profile Section: Visible, showing last saved data
 Visual Indicator: Maybe checkmark icon, muted color

State 3: Edited (Has Changes)
Condition: User modified any field after loading saved data
 Button Display: "Update [Tab] Data"
 Button State: Enabled
 Profile Section: Still visible (showing previous saved version)
 Visual Indicator: Different color (maybe orange/amber) to indicate "pending changes"

State 4: Processing
Condition: Save/Update in progress
 Button Display: "Processing..."
 Button State: Disabled with spinner
 Profile Section: Still visible (showing old data) OR show loading overlay

State 5: Success
Condition: Save completed successfully
 Button Display: "✓ Saved" (briefly, 2 seconds)
 Button State: Disabled
 Profile Section: Updates with new data
 Then transitions to: State 2 (Saved, No Changes)

Change Detection Logic
How do we know if form has changed?
Approach 1: Deep Comparison (Recommended)
javascript
// On component mount, store saved data as reference
const savedDataRef = useRef(savedDataFromDB);

// On any field change, compare current form state to saved reference
const hasChanges = !isEqual(currentFormState, savedDataRef.current);

// Update button state based on hasChanges
if (hasChanges) {
  buttonText = "Update Identity Data";
  buttonEnabled = true;
} else {
  buttonText = "Saved";
  buttonEnabled = false;
}
Approach 2: Dirty Flag (Simpler)
javascript
// Track if ANY field has been edited since load
const [isDirty, setIsDirty] = useState(false);

// On any field onChange event
const handleFieldChange = (value) => {
  setIsDirty(true);
  // update form state
};

// After successful save
const handleSaveSuccess = () => {
  setIsDirty(false);
  savedDataRef.current = currentFormState; // Update reference
};
Recommendation: Use Approach 1 (deep comparison) - more accurate, handles edge cases where user changes then reverts a field.

Profile Section Visibility Rules
Rule 1: On Page Load
javascript
useEffect(() => {
  // Load saved data from database
  const savedData = await loadIdentityData(userId);
  
  if (savedData) {
    // Populate form fields
    setFormState(savedData);
    
    // Show profile section immediately
    setShowProfile(true);
    
    // Store reference for change detection
    savedDataRef.current = savedData;
    
    // Button starts in "Saved" state (disabled)
    setButtonState('saved');
  } else {
    // No saved data
    setShowProfile(false);
    setButtonState('initial');
  }
}, [userId]);
Rule 2: After Save/Update
javascript
const handleSave = async () => {
  setButtonState('processing');
  
  // Save to database
  await saveIdentityData(formState);
  
  // Update reference
  savedDataRef.current = formState;
  
  // Show/update profile section
  setShowProfile(true);
  
  // Button success state
  setButtonState('success');
  
  // After 2 seconds, return to saved state
  setTimeout(() => setButtonState('saved'), 2000);
};
